{"id":"2303.08953","submitter":"Zan Xu","authors":"Zan Xu, Juan J. Alonso, Eric Darve","title":"A numerically stable communication-avoiding s-step GMRES algorithm","comments":"32 pages, 14 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA cs.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Krylov subspace methods are extensively used in scientific computing to solve\nlarge-scale linear systems. However, the performance of these iterative Krylov\nsolvers on modern supercomputers is limited by expensive communication costs.\nThe $s$-step strategy generates a series of $s$ Krylov vectors at a time to\navoid communication. Asymptotically, the $s$-step approach can reduce\ncommunication latency by a factor of $s$. Unfortunately, due to\nfinite-precision implementation, the step size has to be kept small for\nstability. In this work, we tackle the numerical instabilities encountered in\nthe $s$-step GMRES algorithm. By choosing an appropriate polynomial basis and\nblock orthogonalization schemes, we construct a communication avoiding $s$-step\nGMRES algorithm that automatically selects the optimal step size to ensure\nnumerical stability. To further maximize communication savings, we introduce\nscaled Newton polynomials that can increase the step size $s$ to a few hundreds\nfor many problems. An initial step size estimator is also developed to\nefficiently choose the optimal step size for stability. The guaranteed\nstability of the proposed algorithm is demonstrated using numerical\nexperiments. In the process, we also evaluate how the choice of polynomial and\npreconditioning affects the stability limit of the algorithm. Finally, we show\nparallel scalability on more than 14,000 cores in a distributed-memory setting.\nPerfectly linear scaling has been observed in both strong and weak scaling\nstudies with negligible communication costs.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 15 Mar 2023 21:49:18 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 17 Mar 2023 04:54:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-20"}
